ework systematically:\n\n**Evidence Counting — Geopolitical Catalyst:** The Ras Laffan disruption is confirmed by at least five independent desk reports (Geopolitical, Macro, Volatility, Technical, Sentiment) arriving at the same bullish conclusion for partially different reasons — LNG supply shock, TTF arbitrage incentive, EU storage refill urgency, speculative short positioning, and U.S. exporter equity confirmation. This is multiple independent lines, not a single overconfident agent. The Bear correctly notes secondary-source attribution, but the breadth of corroboration across separate data providers (Vortexa, Kpler, Marcellus Drilling News, Trading Economics, NGI, Mansfield Energy, The Edge Singapore) reduces the probability of coordinated error. The TTF surge of 56% to €48.85/MWh is a hard market price signal, not an analyst opinion, and is independently confirmatory.\n\n**Priced-In Check:** The 24h gain of +5.30% and 5-day trend of +8.36% are meaningful momentum signals, but the 'Priced In' rule requires asking whether the catalyst is ongoing. EU storage at 30% (9% below year-ago) creates non-discretionary multi-month refill demand — this is not a one-day event. If the Ras Laffan outage persists even for weeks, the TTF premium over Henry Hub (~€48.85/MWh vs. ~$3.32/MMBtu) creates sustained arbitrage pressure on U.S. LNG terminals operating at maximum feedgas utilization of 19.5 Bcf/d. Partial pricing is the more defensible assumption than full pricing for a supply shock whose duration remains unresolved.\n\n**The 'Priced In' Asymmetry on Capacity Constraint:** The Bear's most powerful argument is that U.S. LNG near-maximum capacity physically blocks incremental volume exports, severing the bullish transmission mechanism. The Geopolitical Report acknowledges this but correctly identifies a logical error in the Bear's framing: maximum capacity utilization IS bullish for Henry Hub in the sense that it guarantees sustained domestic gas draw at the highest possible rate. The capacity ceiling does not suppress Henry Hub — it means every available Bcf/d is being pulled to export terminals at maximum rate. The Bear treats 'no incremental volume increase' as equivalent to 'no price support,' which is a false equivalence explicitly identified in the Geopolitical Report's self-critique.\n\n**Domestic Supply Bearishness — Valid But Time-Lagged:** The Bear's structural case (141 Bcf YoY surplus, 110.2 Bcf/d production, -2.0% domestic demand YoY, rig count highest since July 2023, frack spreads up 22 units) is real and well-evidenced. The Agronomist and Inventory Reports explicitly support a medium-term bearish view (4-12 weeks). However, this structural overhang is measured in months, not days. The geopolitical catalyst is operating on a days-to-weeks timescale that precedes the supply response from rising frack spreads and rig counts. The Bear conflates time horizons — the structural bearish case does not negate a near-term bullish catalyst unless there is evidence the structural factors are immediately suppressing prices right now, which they are not (price just rallied 8.36% in five days).\n\n**Short-Covering vs. New Longs:** The Technical Report's declining OI observation (total -2,920, April front-month -6,636) supports the Bear's short-covering characterization. However, the Sentiment Report adds that CFTC speculative net shorts stand at -198.5K contracts — an extreme short position. Both sides acknowledge this creates short-squeeze vulnerability (doubly weighted per Synthesis Rule 1). The Bear argues short-covering is self-limiting; the Bull argues -198.5K is so extreme that the squeeze has significant runway. The data is ambiguous on which is correct, but the extreme short positioning is a genuine independent bullish signal that the Bear cannot dismiss — it means the market structure itself is coiled for further upside on any sustained geopolitical headline.\n\n**Volatility Cost Awareness — Thesis Strength Downgrade Applied: